✅ 3. Stateless APIs (VERY IMPORTANT)

This is the most important REST rule.

Each request must contain all information needed to process it.

Server does NOT store client session state.


🔎 What does Stateless mean practically?

❌ No server-side sessions
❌ No memory of previous request
❌ No stored login session

Each request must carry authentication info (like JWT token).

Example:

Client logs in → gets token.

After that, every request:

GET /courses
Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6...

Server validates token.
Server does NOT remember user from previous request.


Why Stateless is Good?

Scalable (works well with load balancers)

No session storage needed

Easy horizontal scaling

Microservices friendly

In interview say:

In stateless APIs, the server does not maintain client session state. Each request must carry authentication details like JWT token. This makes APIs scalable and suitable for distributed systems.